<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1871-10-05T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1871-10-05T00:00:00-05:00" n="356" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d356">
                        <head>No. 356.<lb/><hi rend="italic">Mr. <persName type="from">Fish</persName> to Mr. <persName type="to">Stevens</persName>.</hi></head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Department
                                        of State</hi>,<lb/><hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1871-10-05"><hi rend="italic">October</hi> 5,
                                1871</date>.</dateline>
                            <seg rendition="#left">No. 5.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <p><hi rend="smallcaps">Sir</hi>T: I have received your dispatch, No. 5, of
                            the 8th of August last, and have read with much interest the gratifying
                            statement which it contains of the political prospects of a sister
                            republic. The wish of the President for the future of Paraguay, and that
                            the exactions of the governments of Brazil and the Argentine republic in
                            respect to her nationality and territory may be moderate, will be
                            informally communicated to the representatives of those powers.</p>
                        <p>I am, &amp;c, &amp;c,</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>HAMILTON FISH.</signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>